SELECT upsert_knowledge_doc(
  'Accepting and Dismissing Matches',
  'kb/15-matchmaking/04-accepting-and-dismissing.md',
  $kb$# Accepting and Dismissing Matches

Every match I show you is an invitation, not an obligation. You are always in control of which connections you pursue and which ones you pass on. The actions you take -- accepting, dismissing, or saving -- are simple and quick, but they carry real meaning. They help you build the right connections, and they teach me what matters to you so that every future match gets a little more accurate.

Let me walk you through how it all works.

## Accepting a Match

When you see a match that resonates, accepting it is the first step toward building a new connection. What happens next depends on the type of match.

**Person match.** Accepting sends a connection request to the other person. If they accept too, you are connected and can begin messaging each other. I include a brief note about what you have in common to help start the conversation naturally. You are never forced into an awkward cold introduction -- I provide context for both of you.

**Group match.** Accepting joins you to the group. You immediately gain access to the group's discussion space, event calendar, and member list. Most groups welcome new members warmly, and many have introduction threads where you can say hello and share a bit about yourself.

**Event match.** Accepting RSVPs you for the event. You will receive a reminder before it starts, and the event will appear on your schedule. For virtual events, you will get the link to join. For in-person events, you will get the location details.

**Service match.** Accepting takes you to the professional's profile where you can learn more about their credentials and availability, and book a consultation if you choose. Accepting a service match does not automatically commit you to anything -- it simply opens the door.

**Product match.** Accepting takes you to the product page where you can read more details, see reviews from the community, and add it to your cart if you decide to purchase.

**Location match.** Accepting saves the location to your favorites so you can find it easily later. You can also get directions, see hours, and check what other community members have said about the place.

**Live room match.** Accepting adds the session to your schedule and notifies you when it is about to begin. If the room is live right now, accepting takes you directly into the session.

In every case, accepting is a low-commitment first step. It opens a door. You decide how far to walk through it.

## Dismissing a Match

If a match does not feel right, dismissing it is just as simple. Tap dismiss, and the match is removed from your current view.

Dismissing is never penalized. I understand that not every match will resonate, and that is perfectly fine. You might dismiss a match because the timing is wrong, because the focus does not align with your current priorities, or simply because it does not feel like a fit. All of those are valid reasons, and I respect them.

What dismissing does do is inform my future suggestions. When you consistently dismiss certain types of matches, I learn from that pattern. If you rarely engage with product matches, I will reduce their frequency. If you dismiss matches from a certain geographic area, I adjust. Over time, your dismissals help me filter out what is not useful so that your match feed becomes increasingly relevant.

I never dismiss a match on your behalf. Every card stays until you act on it, save it, or a new day brings fresh suggestions.

## Saving for Later

Sometimes a match looks interesting but the timing is not right. Maybe you want to attend that event but need to check your schedule first. Maybe a person match looks promising but you want to think about it before reaching out. That is what "save for later" is for.

Saved matches are stored in your matchmaking section where you can revisit them anytime. They do not expire. If you save a person match today and come back to it next week, you can still accept and send a connection request. If you save an event match, you will still be able to RSVP as long as the event has not already happened.

Saving is a useful habit because it prevents good matches from slipping through the cracks on busy days. I recommend using it whenever something catches your eye but you are not ready to act immediately.

## How Your Choices Shape Future Matches

This is one of the most important things to understand about the matching system: your actions are the primary feedback loop that makes it smarter.

**Accepting teaches me what you want.** When you accept a person match with shared fitness goals, I learn that fitness alignment is important to you. When you accept a group focused on nutrition, I know that topic matters. When you consistently accept event matches in your local area, I prioritize geographic proximity in future suggestions.

**Dismissing teaches me what you do not want.** If you regularly dismiss professional service matches, I understand that you prefer self-directed progress right now. If you skip product suggestions, I reduce them. If you dismiss matches with low scores, I raise my threshold for what I show you.

**Deeper engagement reinforces patterns.** It is not just the initial accept or dismiss that matters. What happens after also teaches me. If you accept a person match and that connection leads to regular conversations, shared challenge participation, or attending the same events, I understand that the factors behind that match were strong. I look for more connections with similar alignment. If an accepted match leads to no further engagement, I note that too and adjust.

**Saving tells me about timing.** When you save matches rather than acting on them immediately, I learn that you are interested but selective. I may highlight similar options in the future while respecting that you prefer to take your time with new connections.

All of this happens quietly in the background. You do not need to configure anything or explain your preferences in words. Your actions speak clearly, and I listen carefully.

## A Note on Connection Quality

I want to encourage you to be intentional about the matches you accept. It is natural to accept everything, but the research on social bonds and longevity suggests that depth matters more than breadth. A few meaningful connections will do more for your health than dozens of shallow ones.

Take a moment to read the "why this match" explanation on each card. Consider whether this connection aligns with where you are in your journey. Trust your instincts. If a match does not feel right, there is no pressure to accept it. Tomorrow will bring new opportunities.

The goal is not to maximize connections. The goal is to build a small, strong, longevity-aligned network of people, communities, and resources that genuinely support the life you want to live.

## Related Topics

- [Your Daily Matches](kb-en-15-02) -- How fresh matches are delivered every day and where to find them
- [Match Preferences](kb-en-15-05) -- How to customize the kinds of matches you see$kb$,
  'markdown',
  ARRAY['accept', 'dismiss', 'matches', 'feedback', 'matchmaking', 'all', 'live']
);

-- [89/116] kb-en-15-05
SELECT upsert_knowledge_doc(
  'Match Preferences',
  'kb/15-matchmaking/05-match-preferences.md',
  $kb$# Match Preferences

While my matching system learns a great deal from your behavior -- the matches you accept, dismiss, and engage with -- you also have direct control over the types of connections I suggest. Your match preferences are a set of filters and settings that shape how I search for matches on your behalf. Think of them as guardrails: they tell me what to prioritize, what to include, and what to leave out.

Let me explain each preference and how it affects your experience.

## Match Types

You can choose which of the seven match types you want to see in your daily matches. By default, all types are active: person, group, event, service, product, location, and live room. But you might prefer to focus on certain types at different times.

If you are in a phase where building personal connections is your priority, you can emphasize person and group matches. If you are looking for professional guidance, you can turn up service matches. If you prefer to discover events and live rooms, you can weight those more heavily.

You can adjust these at any time, and I will respond immediately. Turning off a match type does not mean I will never surface it again -- it just means it will not appear in your daily feed until you turn it back on. I may still mention relevant opportunities through our conversations if something genuinely important comes up.

## Geographic Range

Geography matters for longevity connections, especially when it comes to in-person interaction. You can set a preferred geographic range that tells me how far to look when generating matches.

**Local.** If you want matches close to home -- people you could meet for a walk, events in your neighborhood, wellness centers nearby -- set a tight range. This is ideal if you value real-world connection and want to build a local longevity community.

**Regional.** A broader range captures opportunities within your wider area -- a city-level or state-level scope. This is useful if you live in a less densely populated area or if you are open to traveling a short distance for the right event or connection.

**Global.** If geography is not a factor for you -- if you are comfortable with virtual friendships, online group participation, and digital events -- you can open the range to include anyone in the Vitanaland community worldwide.

Your geographic preference applies primarily to person, group, event, location, and live room matches. Product and service matches may draw from a wider area when the service is delivered virtually or the product can be shipped.

## Health Focus Areas

This is one of the most impactful preferences you can set. Health focus areas tell me which of your health pillars or wellness topics should take priority in matching.

You can select from focus areas like nutrition, exercise, sleep, hydration, mental health, stress management, strength training, cardiovascular fitness, cognitive health, social connection, and more. When you activate a focus area, I give extra weight to matches that relate to that topic.

For example, if you set "sleep" as a health focus, you will see more matches related to sleep -- people who have improved their sleep quality, groups focused on recovery and rest, events about sleep science, professionals who specialize in sleep health, and products designed for better rest.

You can set multiple focus areas, and I will balance across them. I recommend updating your focus areas as your goals evolve. What matters most to you this month might shift next month, and your matches should shift with it.

## Age Range

For person matches, you can set a preferred age range. This is entirely optional. Some people prefer to connect with peers in a similar life stage. Others find value in intergenerational connections -- learning from someone older or mentoring someone younger.

If you set an age range, I will prioritize person matches within that range. If you leave it open, I will match based purely on longevity alignment without regard to age. In practice, the strongest matches often cross age boundaries because health goals and lifestyle values are not limited to any generation.

## Language

If you speak multiple languages or prefer to connect with people who share your primary language, you can set a language preference. This is especially useful in a global community where members communicate in many languages.

When a language preference is set, I prioritize matches where smooth communication is likely. For groups and events, I surface those conducted in your preferred language. For person matches, I look for shared language capability.

## How Preferences Shape the Algorithm

Your preferences do not replace the algorithm -- they shape it. The matching system still considers your Vitana Index, your health goals, your community activity, your lifestyle patterns, and your accept and dismiss history. Preferences add an additional layer of guidance on top of that intelligence.

Think of it this way: the algorithm finds the matches. Your preferences tell me which matches to bring to the front of the line.

If you set tight preferences -- a narrow age range, a small geographic area, a single health focus -- your daily matches will be fewer but more focused. If you keep preferences broad, you will see a wider variety of suggestions. Neither approach is better or worse. It depends on what kind of experience you are looking for right now.

## Updating Preferences Over Time

I encourage you to revisit your match preferences periodically. Your longevity journey is not static, and your matching experience should not be either.

Maybe six months ago you were focused on nutrition and wanted local connections. Now you have shifted your attention to mental health and you are open to global connections for the first time. Updating your preferences takes only a moment, and the impact on your daily matches is immediate.

You can access your match preferences from the Matchmaking section -- look for the settings or preferences option. Changes take effect starting with your next batch of daily matches.

## The ORB Learns Too

Beyond the explicit preferences you set, I also learn from your behavior. This is worth repeating because it is important: your accepts, dismisses, saves, and engagement patterns all refine the matching system in ways that go deeper than any single preference setting.

If you accept a person match who shares your interest in cold exposure, I do not need you to add "cold exposure" as a health focus. I already learned it from your action. If you consistently attend events on weekday evenings, I do not need you to set a time preference. I adjust naturally.

Your preferences and your behavior work together. The preferences set the boundaries. Your actions paint the picture within those boundaries. Over time, the two converge into a matching experience that feels like it genuinely understands you -- because it does.

## My Recommendation

If you are just getting started, I suggest keeping your preferences relatively open. Let the system learn from your behavior for the first few weeks. Accept the matches that feel right, dismiss the ones that do not, and let me calibrate to your natural patterns.

Once you have a sense of what resonates, tighten your preferences to sharpen the focus. Turn off match types you do not need right now. Narrow your geographic range if local connection is what you want. Set health focus areas that reflect your current priorities.

And remember -- you can always adjust. Your preferences are a living part of your Vitanaland experience, just like the rest of your longevity journey.

## Related Topics

- [How Matching Works](kb-en-15-01) -- The full algorithm behind every match I suggest
- [Accepting and Dismissing Matches](kb-en-15-04) -- How your choices directly refine future suggestions$kb$,
  'markdown',
  ARRAY['preferences', 'settings', 'filters', 'matchmaking', 'all', 'live']
);

